Introduction¶

This dataset contains information on all the space missions in human history (from 1957 to August 2022). It was gotten from Maven Analytics Data Playground.

The dataset contains a csv table with 4,631 records, one for each space mission. Each record contains details on each mission's name, location, date, and status of the launch, the company responsible, and the price, status, and name of the rocket.

The dataset will be wrangled, analyzed and visualized to find out the patterns and trends in mission status of space missions, rocket status and price over the years and across countries.

Column names and their description¶

  • Company: Company responsible for the space mission
  • Location: Location of the launch
  • Date: Date of the launch
  • Time: Time of the launch (UTC)
  • Rocket: Name of the rocket used for the mission
  • Mission: Name of the space mission (or missions)
  • RocketStatus: Status of the rocket as of August 2022 (Active or Inactive)
  • Price: Cost of the rocket in millions of US dollars
  • MissionStatus: Status of the mission (Success, Failure, Partial Failure, Prelaunch Failure)

Quality Issues

  • Missing values in Time and Price columns
  • Erroneous column datatypes (Date, Time, RocketStatus, Price, and MissionStatus)
    • Datetime: Date and Time
    • Categorical: RocketStatus(Active or Inactive) and MissionStatus (Success, Failure, Partial Failure, Prelaunch Failure))
    • Numerical/Float: Price
  • One duplicate (index number: 3531)
  • Change column names to lowercase

Tidiness Issues

  • Launch site and country should be separated from the Location column into two columns
  • Date and Time should be combined to one column
  • Other: A column for year to be created

Issue #2: Tidiness Issues¶

  • Launch site and country should be separated from the Location column into its own column
  • Date and Time should be combined to one column
  • Other: A column for year to be created

1. Launch site and country should be separated from the Location column into its own column

Define:

Create two columns Launch_Site and Country from the Location column using .rsplit() function. Remove white space character from the Country column. Then, drop the Location column.

Code

In [12]:
# splitting the `Location` column into new columns, `Site` and `Country`
space_missions_clean[['Launch_Site', 'Country']] = space_missions_clean['Location'].str.rsplit(',', expand=True, n=1)
space_w_nulls[['Launch_Site', 'Country']] = space_w_nulls['Location'].str.rsplit(',', expand=True, n=1)

# stripping white space character off the `Country` column values
space_missions_clean['Country'] = space_missions_clean['Country'].str.strip()
space_w_nulls['Country'] = space_w_nulls['Country'].str.strip()

# dropping the `Location` column
space_missions_clean.drop('Location', axis=1, inplace=True)
space_w_nulls.drop('Location', axis=1, inplace=True)

2. Date and Time should be combined to one column

Define:

Convert only the Date datatype to datetime. Then, drop Time column as combining the null values of the Time to Date deletes all Date data in the dataset copy we are allowing to have null values (i.e. space_w_nulls). Also, Time will not be used in the analysis.

Code

In [14]:
# converting `Date` to datetime dtype
space_missions_clean['Date'] = pd.to_datetime(space_missions_clean['Date'])
space_w_nulls['Date'] = pd.to_datetime(space_w_nulls['Date'])

# dropping `Time` column
col = ['Time']
space_missions_clean.drop(col, axis=1, inplace=True)
space_w_nulls.drop(col, axis=1, inplace=True)

Issue #3: Quality Issues¶

  • Erroneous column datatypes (Date, Time, RocketStatus, Price, and MissionStatus)
    • Datetime: Date and Time
    • Categorical: RocketStatus(Active or Inactive) and MissionStatus (Success, Failure, Partial Failure, Prelaunch Failure)
    • Numerical/Float: Price
    • Note : Now that a new Country column has been created, convert to categorical datatype.
  • One duplicate (index number: 3531)
  • Change column names to lowercase

1. Erroneous datatypes (Date, Time, RocketStatus, Price, and MissionStatus...plus Country)

Define:

Change RocketStatus and Country to unordered categorical datatypes, MissionStatus to ordered categorical datatype and Price to float datatype. Datehas already been converted to datetime datatype and Time has been dropped, so they won't be addressed here.

Code

In [19]:
# converting `RocketStatus` and `Country` to unordered categorical dtype
unordered_cat_columns = ['RocketStatus', 'Country']
space_missions_clean[unordered_cat_columns] = space_missions_clean[unordered_cat_columns].astype('category')
space_w_nulls[unordered_cat_columns] = space_w_nulls[unordered_cat_columns].astype('category')

# converting `MissionStatus` to ordered categorical dtype 
ordinal_status = ['Prelaunch Failure','Partial Failure', 'Failure', 'Success']
cat_type = CategoricalDtype(categories= ordinal_status, ordered=True)
space_missions_clean['MissionStatus'] = space_missions_clean['MissionStatus'].astype(cat_type)
space_w_nulls['MissionStatus'] = space_w_nulls['MissionStatus'].astype(cat_type)

# converting`Price` to float dtype
space_missions_clean['Price'] = space_missions_clean['Price'].str.replace(',', '').astype('float')
space_w_nulls['Price'] = space_w_nulls['Price'].str.replace(',', '').astype('float')

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

There are 4630 space mission entries in the dataset with 9 columns. All variables pre-cleaning are non_numeric and contain null values in two columns with a duplicated row. After wrangling and cleaning, dataset pares down to 1258 mission entries with 10 features (company, launch_site, country, date, rocket, price, rocket_status, mission, mission_status, and year). The cleaned dataset has 2 numeric variables, 3 categorical variables and 4 object/string variables. Of the three categorical variables, one (mission_status) is an ordered categorical variable with the following levels:

(worst) ——> (best)

mission_status: Prelaunch Failure, Partial Failure, Failure, Success

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

The main feature of this dataset is the mission status of rockets as well the rocket status. I'm in interested in whether the success of space missions can be predicted by the variables in the dataset; and if so, the degree of prediction, and how it varies geographically across nations.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

I expect to uncover the effect of price, year and rocket status in determining mission success and whether there is any noteworthy relationship between those variables.

# defining a function to plot simple count without order argument set
def simple_count(column_name):
    """"This function plots a simple count of plots """
    base_color = sb.color_palette()[0]
    sb.countplot(data = space_missions_clean, x = column_name, color = base_color)
    plt.xlabel(f"{column_name.replace('_', ' ').title()}", fontsize=12)
    plt.ylabel("Count", fontsize=12)
    plt.title(f"Distribution of {column_name.replace('_', ' ').title()}", fontsize=15);

In [40]:
# defining a function that plot counts with the order argument set
def ordered_counts(column_name):
    """Simple count of plots with the order argument set"""
    plt.figure(figsize=[12, 6])
    base_color = sb.color_palette()[0]
    ordered = space_missions_clean[column_name].value_counts().index
    plt.title(f"Frequency of {column_name.title()}", fontsize=15)            
    if column_name == 'country':
        sb.countplot(data = space_missions_clean, y = column_name, color = base_color, order = ordered);
        plt.ylabel(f"{column_name.title()}", fontsize=12)
        plt.xlabel("Count", fontsize=12)
    else:
        sb.countplot(data = space_missions_clean, x = column_name, color = base_color, order = ordered);
        plt.xticks(rotation= 90)
        plt.xlabel(f"{column_name.title()}", fontsize=12)
        plt.ylabel("Count", fontsize=12)

# defining function to plot the violin and boxplots of categorical and numeric variables"
def violin_boxplots(first_var, second_var):
    """A function that plots the violin and boxplots of categorical and numeric variables"""
    # setting uniform color
    base_color = sb.color_palette()[0]
    
    plt.figure(figsize = [12, 6])
    plt.suptitle(f"{first_var.replace('_', ' ').title()} vs. {second_var.replace('_', ' ').title()} Relationship", fontsize=15);
    
   
    country_plot_order = space_missions_clean.country.value_counts().index
    plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)
    if first_var == 'country':
        sb.violinplot(data = space_missions_clean, x = first_var, y = second_var,
              inner= 'quartile', color = base_color, order = country_plot_order)
        plt.xticks(rotation = 45);
    else:
        sb.violinplot(data = space_missions_clean, x = first_var, y = second_var, inner= 'quartile', color = base_color);    
    plt.xlabel(f"{first_var.replace('_', ' ').title()}", fontsize=12)
    plt.ylabel(f"{second_var.replace('_', ' ').title()}", fontsize=12)

        
    plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)
    if first_var == 'country':
        sb.boxplot(data = space_missions_clean, x = first_var , y = second_var, color = base_color, order = country_plot_order)
        plt.xticks(rotation = 45);
    else:
        sb.boxplot(data = space_missions_clean, x = first_var, y = second_var, color = base_color);
    plt.xlabel(f"{first_var.replace('_', ' ').title()}", fontsize=12)
    plt.ylabel(f"{second_var.replace('_', ' ').title()}", fontsize=12)
        
    plt.show()

# defining a function to plot a clustered bar chart of two cat variables
def clustered_barchart(first_var, second_var):
    """This function plots a clustered bar chart of two categorical variables"""
    if second_var == 'country':
        country_order = space_missions_clean.country.value_counts().index
        sb.countplot(data = space_missions_clean, x = first_var, 
                     hue = 'country', hue_order = country_order)
    else:
        sb.countplot(data = space_missions_clean, x = first_var, hue = second_var);
    if first_var == 'mission_status':
        plt.legend(loc = 'upper left')
    else:
        plt.legend(loc = 'upper right');
    plt.xlabel(first_var.replace('_', ' ').title(), fontsize=12)
    plt.ylabel("Count", fontsize=12)
In [69]:
# defining a function to plot a heatmap of two cat variables
def cat_heatmap(first_var, second_var):
    """This function plots a heatmap of two categorical variables"""
    # checking combination of variables with groupby() and size() as a pandas series
    ct_counts = space_missions_clean.groupby([first_var, second_var]).size()
    # converting the series into a dataframe with reset_index()
    ct_counts = ct_counts.reset_index(name = 'count')
    # rearranging data by pivoting into rows and columns with values in the cells
    ct_counts = ct_counts.pivot(index = first_var, columns = second_var, values = 'count')
    
    # plotting heatmap with the dataframe and annotating the counts in the cells as decimals
    sb.heatmap(ct_counts, annot = True, fmt = 'd');
    plt.xlabel(f"{second_var.replace('_', ' ').title()}", fontsize=12)
    plt.ylabel(f"{first_var.replace('_', ' ').title()}", fontsize=12)
In [72]:
# defining a function that subplots the clustered bar and heatmap plot functions
def bar_heat_subplots(first_var, second_var):
    """This function to subplots the clustered bar chart and heatmap functions of two categorical variables"""
    plt.figure(figsize = [16, 8])
    plt.suptitle(f"Distribution in counts of {first_var.replace('_', ' ').title()} by {second_var.replace('_', ' ').title()} ", fontsize=18);
    
    plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)
    clustered_barchart(first_var, second_var)
    
    plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)
    cat_heatmap(first_var, second_var)
    
    plt.show()

Conclusions¶

The distribution of the variable of interest, the mission_status shows that about 95% of all space missions were successful; indicating a very high mission success rate with the number of active rockets twice the number of retired rockets. In this dataset, which the cleaned dataset with no null values, the USA is the country with the most launched space missions followed by China in second place and France in the third place.

In comparison with the original dataset which has some null price values, there seems to be a resurgence in space mission programs in recent years especially in the 2020's which show the highest space mission programs in human history.

There is a weak negative correlation between year and price because after the year 1990, a significant decline in the price of rockets till date is seen. From the late 2010's upwards, a high density of rockets with lower prices in use is observed.

With an unusually high price for a rocket at 5 billion USD and the lowest price at 2.5 million dollars, most rocket prices lie below 500 million dollars. The rocket price range of active rockets lie below 500 million USD while the rockets with the outlier price range of between 1000 - 5000 million USD have all been retired. There is a very strong indication that cheaper or cost-effective rockets is the way forward in the next wave of the space race.

Resources used during cleaning

  • pandas.Series.dt.year to extract year from date values.

  • Extracting year from pandas datetime.

  • Re-ordering columns.

  • Right splitting columns and adding element to new column.

  • Replacing commas and converting to floats.

  • Combining date time and changing its datatype.
